WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.199 --> 00:00:04.759
&gt;&gt;Female speaker: Hi everyone, I'm Heather
Stillman and on behalf of the Authors at Google

00:00:04.759 --> 00:00:11.440
team here at Los Angeles, I'm honored to introduce
to you today, my cousin, Karen Krasne, the

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:14.340
owner and executive Chef of Extraordinary
Desserts.

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:19.500
She will be speaking today about her recent
book, Extraordinary Cakes.

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:25.360
Her cakes have graced the cover of Bon Appetite
and Forums recognized her as one of the country's

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:27.260
Ten Best Pastry Chefs.

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:34.020
She has been featured in New York Times, Gourmet,
Sunset and the Los Angeles Times, among other

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:35.090
publications.

00:00:35.090 --> 00:00:40.390
In 1988, Karen opened Extraordinary Desserts
in San Diego.

00:00:40.390 --> 00:00:47.720
A year later the eatery was in such demand
that Karen was able to expand from ten seats

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:54.680
to sixty-five seats, and in 2004, she opened
a second location in San Diego's Little Italy.

00:00:54.680 --> 00:01:00.760
Karen graduated with a degree from the University
of Hawaii in Food and Human Nutrition, and

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:06.060
went on to study pastry making at Le Cordon
Bleu in Paris, France.

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:13.109
She has brought some of these fabulous desserts
to share with us today, and now, Karen Krasne.

00:01:13.109 --> 00:01:16.369
&gt;&gt;Karen Krasne: Thank you.

00:01:16.369 --> 00:01:17.990
[Audience applauds]

00:01:17.990 --> 00:01:24.049
&gt;&gt;Karen: So I'm just going to kinda start
with the concept of what Extraordinary Desserts

00:01:24.049 --> 00:01:26.340
is and what it's become.

00:01:26.340 --> 00:01:31.969
When we started in 1988, We just did desserts
at our one location that now seats a hundred

00:01:31.969 --> 00:01:35.320
and it's desserts seven
days a week.

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:40.460
And then we opened a second location in Little
Italy, where we seat about 250

00:01:40.460 --> 00:01:46.069
people, and both locations are open until
about eleven at night, midnight on the weekends.

00:01:46.069 --> 00:01:51.539
And at the bigger location
we do have food and wine, paninis and alcohol

00:01:51.539 --> 00:01:55.429
and things like that so that we don't just
have the desserts, so we've

00:01:55.429 --> 00:02:00.740
become two different places that people love
to go to one or the other, and they're really

00:02:00.740 --> 00:02:03.990
fanatical about which one
they prefer.

00:02:03.990 --> 00:02:10.069
So it's interesting because some like The
Original, as it's known, and some like The

00:02:10.069 --> 00:02:11.069
New.

00:02:11.069 --> 00:02:14.150
So I want to go
back a little bit on my background, I know

00:02:14.150 --> 00:02:15.890
Heather touched on it.

00:02:15.890 --> 00:02:24.050
I am born and raised in San Diego, and I took
off at about seventeen for Hawaii, and somehow

00:02:24.050 --> 00:02:27.409
got a degree about eight years later.

00:02:27.409 --> 00:02:32.629
And it was Human Nutrition and
it was under the Tropical Ag genre at the

00:02:32.629 --> 00:02:35.349
University of Hawaii, so I think that's where
a lot of my tropical

00:02:35.349 --> 00:02:42.560
agriculture comes in here, and from there
you pretty much-- this was way way way back

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:47.159
in the old days, so you sort of
had to go and get a Master's in Public Health

00:02:47.159 --> 00:02:51.970
or things like that and it just didn't sound
like that was good for me,

00:02:51.970 --> 00:02:56.010
so I took off to France, and spent about a
year and half there at different schools,

00:02:56.010 --> 00:02:58.299
Cordon Bleu was one of them.

00:02:58.299 --> 00:03:01.140
And
then came back to San Diego and started making

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:05.540
cakes for like Nieman Marcus, some other very
high end establishments,

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:10.750
and just sort of dropped off, peddled, you
know basically peddling to them, and built

00:03:10.750 --> 00:03:15.099
up a clientele enough that I
could open up a store that had ten seats.

00:03:15.099 --> 00:03:18.739
And from there the ten seats grew to sixty-five,
and a hundred and then the

00:03:18.739 --> 00:03:21.240
second store, and so on and so forth.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:27.120
So I don't know, we're in about twenty-two
years of business at this point, and

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:33.140
I decided to write the book, which took maybe
two years to write.

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:35.770
And I felt that it was necessary to document
the

00:03:35.770 --> 00:03:41.180
type of work that we do because it is so different
from what you see pretty much anywhere in

00:03:41.180 --> 00:03:45.931
the States and then,
likewise in Europe, where I just was for a

00:03:45.931 --> 00:03:49.040
couple of weeks and just got back ten days
ago.

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:52.311
So what I think
what we do that's so different is that we

00:03:52.311 --> 00:03:57.480
really tried to use a lot of color, and a
lot of fresh whatever is going

00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:02.959
on in the market, in terms of flowers and
fruits, and what not, and we also try to do

00:04:02.959 --> 00:04:07.670
a spin on flavors so that it's
not just the typical things you'd expect,

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:13.019
chocolate with raspberries, we infuse things,
we use herbs, we use a lot of

00:04:13.019 --> 00:04:18.330
yuzu, we use Matcha tea, we tend to follow
the patterns of desserts that are going on

00:04:18.330 --> 00:04:24.160
more, say, in the East coast,
because I am in New York quite a bit, and

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:30.650
then in Paris, where I think is where pastry
really has been born, and is

00:04:30.650 --> 00:04:37.060
really studied, and has a metamorphosis beyond
anywhere else that I've ever seen.

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:41.780
So I just finished a class over there which
we call stagez.

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:47.040
And it was three days and eighty hours, I
mean three days,

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:50.500
eighty recipes, thirty five hours.

00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:56.840
And it was really really incredible what is
happening that is the same as it was

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:03.900
twenty-five years ago, but it's just become
more flavorful, more simplified, less sugar,

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:04.920
less fat.

00:05:04.920 --> 00:05:07.800
They're following
the same buzz words we're following here,

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:10.810
but it's introduced in a way that's a little
bit more elegant over there.

00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:14.010
Nobody feels that they're skipping or missing
something.

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:18.540
So today I thought that I would make probably
the easiest

00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:20.670
recipe in the book.

00:05:20.670 --> 00:05:26.020
The recipes tend to take about two or three
days for preparation, because they're cakes,

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:28.471
and then
crèmes and then different layers that you

00:05:28.471 --> 00:05:32.380
build on it and then you end up freezing the
product, and then you take it

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:36.340
out the day you're going to serve it and you
finish it up, so that it's nice and hard when

00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:40.750
you finish it, so you get
really clean edges like these cakes over here.

00:05:40.750 --> 00:05:44.800
If you try to make a cake, and put the frosting
in it and put the next

00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:48.900
cake layer on it, and frost it and put another,
and then you try to finish it, I mean it's

00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:53.410
all gobbledy-gook and
uneven and you know people always wonder "how

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:55.200
are your cakes so perfect?"

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:58.690
It's because they had a stage where they
got to be frozen for eight hours to twelve

00:05:58.690 --> 00:06:02.730
hours to overnight and that's one of the key
things in the book.

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:06.690
But not
everyone has two or three days to make a cake

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:10.550
so there's a few things in the book, one is
the bread pudding.

00:06:10.550 --> 00:06:13.530
I'm also
gonna show you, not going to show you how

00:06:13.530 --> 00:06:16.360
to make it, but this is an element in the
book, this white chocolate

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:20.130
mousse, instead of having to make the cake
that might take three days, you could just

00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:24.791
make the mousse, and I've
simply either put it in a large form in a

00:06:24.791 --> 00:06:29.310
glass so you could use any kind of wine glass,
goblet, that kind of thing,

00:06:29.310 --> 00:06:33.570
or these are simple votive candles that you
can pick up at Smart and Final.

00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:37.560
You can be as creative as you want with
some of the elements of the book and not have

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:39.530
to make cakes with them.

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:45.620
So, I tried to break it down so that it does
seem like you wanna try for some of the hard

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:50.150
projects, but then at the same time, I don't
want to make it so, you

00:06:50.150 --> 00:06:53.350
know, full of effort that you don't even want
to open the book.

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:59.240
So, the bread pudding basically has about
5 ingredients in it, and so I take the cream

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:06.410
and the milk, I just put it
together in the pot, and I hope I have heat

00:07:06.410 --> 00:07:16.520
going, let's see, it seems like it, okay and
then the sugar is going in

00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:25.570
the bowl with the egg yolks, I don't know
if you all use vanilla beans or if you use

00:07:25.570 --> 00:07:26.570
vanilla extract.

00:07:26.570 --> 00:07:28.590
If you're
using a vanilla bean, you definitely want

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:32.310
it at room temperature, so it's really nice
and pliable.

00:07:32.310 --> 00:07:37.000
And then when you
cut it open, you're going to use a sharp little

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.970
knife like this to cut it open, and then when
you scrape out the

00:07:39.970 --> 00:07:44.330
meat, you use the back of the knife, not the
sharp, because you don't want the pith, which

00:07:44.330 --> 00:07:46.660
would be like getting the
pith from an orange or a lemon that's kind

00:07:46.660 --> 00:07:51.370
of bitter, so it's real important that your
knife is nice and sharp to cut

00:07:51.370 --> 00:07:57.250
open the bean like this and then it's going
to expose this really glistening, sort of

00:07:57.250 --> 00:07:58.840
dark meat.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:02.710
Those are the seeds
and are the most delicious part and the reason

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:05.690
why you pay so much for a vanilla bean.

00:08:05.690 --> 00:08:10.380
So, once I have that out, I
just go ahead and put it in the pot in the

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:16.120
cream and the milk, and then I put the whole
bean in there as well.

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:19.460
And
then I've got my yolks and my sugar going

00:08:19.460 --> 00:08:23.390
here and I just mix those up, and we're going
to wait for the cream and the

00:08:23.390 --> 00:08:31.150
milk to come to almost a boil, and then we'll
pour that into the egg yolk mixture, we'll

00:08:31.150 --> 00:08:34.300
strain it, and that's
basically the crème brulee.

00:08:34.300 --> 00:08:39.010
So that's an element that you could take as
crème brulee and put in into little porcelain

00:08:39.010 --> 00:08:44.860
dishes and bake it off in a water bath in
the oven, and you don't even have to go further

00:08:44.860 --> 00:08:46.880
into this other aspect of
it.

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:52.500
One of the things that I do use, that make
it a little bit easier for you, is they're

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:59.110
store bought croissants, and
you need about ten of this size.

00:08:59.110 --> 00:09:04.840
And, you know, if they're kind of beige-y,
not real baked off, go ahead and put them

00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:08.630
back in your oven and bake them real firm,
because they're going to soak up all this

00:09:08.630 --> 00:09:13.510
crème brulee and get nice and
crusty, and it's nice and juicy.

00:09:13.510 --> 00:09:20.860
So the flat ones that are not, you know, real
bronzed in color, you definitely want

00:09:20.860 --> 00:09:23.530
to bake those again.

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:28.180
And probably put them in at about, I don't
know, three fifty for about ten minutes, and

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:29.610
get them
nice and colored.

00:09:29.610 --> 00:09:34.070
And you'll see that they're, you can see inside
of the croissant, you see all the texture

00:09:34.070 --> 00:09:35.070
in it.

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:38.890
When they’re real mushy, you know, like
someone flattened 'em out, they're not going

00:09:38.890 --> 00:09:42.280
to be as fabulous, so you
definitely want this puffier kind.

00:09:42.280 --> 00:09:43.280
Yes?

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:44.280
&gt;&gt;female #1: So how drastic is it between
using real vanilla versus vanilla syrup or

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:45.280
even fake vanilla
extract?

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:58.150
I can guess what you're probably going to
tell me, but...

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:00.280
&gt;&gt;Karen: I know.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:05.730
So the question is about a vanilla bean, versus
an extract, or fake vanilla or vanilla syrup.

00:10:05.730 --> 00:10:08.320
Well,
I mean, your desserts are only as good as

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:10.130
your product.

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:14.840
So I don't know that in this it's a deal breaker
to use a

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:19.900
real vanilla bean but if you're making vanilla
ice cream, if you're making vanilla mousse,

00:10:19.900 --> 00:10:23.070
if you're making vanilla
sauce, that would be when I would say you

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:25.170
should probably go buy the vanilla beans.

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:28.779
But in this sort of a situation,
I am using such good chocolate, and this is

00:10:28.779 --> 00:10:31.900
valrhona, and I don't know if all of you know
about valrhona chocolate,

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:38.900
but it's from the Rhone region in the Val
area of France, and there's probably, I don't

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:43.840
know, twenty-five different
grades of chocolate, everything from fifty

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:47.630
percent all the way up into eighty-two percent,
and you can pick and

00:10:47.630 --> 00:10:48.780
choose your flavors.

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:53.980
We sell ten different styles at Extraordinary
Desserts, I am sure you can find it here at

00:10:53.980 --> 00:11:00.070
Surface, but it's excellent chocolate and
the one I am using today is sixty-one percent

00:11:00.070 --> 00:11:05.660
and it just has a really true
chocolate flavor, no berries, or jasmine or

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:08.610
coffee notes in it, it's just real clear chocolate.

00:11:08.610 --> 00:11:14.310
Okay good, this
is-- thank you.

00:11:14.310 --> 00:11:15.310
[laughs]

00:11:15.310 --> 00:11:18.110
[tapping on pot]

00:11:18.110 --> 00:11:23.750
So, these are going to be our filler, the
chocolate and the croissants, and once this

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:29.040
is finished, we'll put half of
the crème brulee in the bottom, I use this

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:33.230
in the book, this kind of a mold, and you
can either use this kind of a

00:11:33.230 --> 00:11:37.610
thing or you can use an oval.

00:11:37.610 --> 00:11:44.260
Here's what this one comes up, it's great
for a brunch buffet, this is great family

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:45.260
style.

00:11:45.260 --> 00:11:47.590
It's really however you want to present it.

00:11:47.590 --> 00:11:52.410
You can also build them in little dishes that
are porcelain like

00:11:52.410 --> 00:11:54.800
that.

00:11:54.800 --> 00:11:58.600
Same kind of a thing, you just put the crème
brulee in, put the croissants in , then the

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:00.130
chocolate and then
layer them again like that, and then bake

00:12:00.130 --> 00:12:03.960
it off and you're right there.

