00:15:48.850 --> 00:15:52.330
Because let's say you do want this for crème
brulee, you don't want to make bread pudding,

00:15:52.330 --> 00:15:56.529
you definitely want everything to be strained
out of here, and it's

00:15:56.529 --> 00:16:01.540
nice to have like at the end, you've got the
grains from that vanilla, all the seeds, and

00:16:01.540 --> 00:16:04.040
it's good to have all that
in there and people see that you're using

00:16:04.040 --> 00:16:07.040
real vanilla beans.

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:12.110
So, I think this will be easy to see.

00:16:12.110 --> 00:16:20.380
So we're
going to put half of it into the bottom, and

00:16:20.380 --> 00:16:33.160
then half of the croissants, and then I take,
this is two cups of

00:16:33.160 --> 00:16:41.240
chocolate, so it's a lot of chocolate, so
even if your croissants aren't flavorful,

00:16:41.240 --> 00:16:42.410
they will be.

00:16:42.410 --> 00:16:44.270
[audience laughs]

00:16:44.270 --> 00:16:48.170
And then I go ahead and I take the rest of
the croissants and I put it on, so it's like

00:16:48.170 --> 00:16:49.680
you're building a sandwich.

00:16:49.680 --> 00:16:53.700
&gt;&gt;female #3: Can I ask why you have the tin
foil on there?

00:16:53.700 --> 00:16:56.750
&gt;&gt;Karen: Because otherwise, my crème brulee
is going to seep out.

00:16:56.750 --> 00:16:59.600
So while we were testing this for the book,
we...it

00:16:59.600 --> 00:17:02.970
seeped out a few times, and I'm like, hmm,
this isn't going to be good.

00:17:02.970 --> 00:17:03.970
&gt;&gt;female #3: From where?

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:05.889
&gt;&gt;Karen: From the bottom, because it has a
push out bottom.

00:17:05.889 --> 00:17:07.199
&gt;&gt; female #3: Oh right.

00:17:07.199 --> 00:17:08.199
I forgot.

00:17:08.199 --> 00:17:21.539
&gt;&gt;Karen: And then, I'm gonna put this in here,
and then you just go ahead and fill up.

00:17:21.539 --> 00:17:24.829
So it seems like, oh my gosh
that's a lot of liquid but that's why it's

00:17:24.829 --> 00:17:33.269
so wonderfully custardy and then the chocolate's
melted and, it's, we

00:17:33.269 --> 00:17:41.120
make this everyday at the store, and everyday
I walk by it and I go, hmm, is anybody looking,

00:17:41.120 --> 00:17:45.720
and I like
grab-- because the best part is like this

00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:47.460
real crusty.

00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:48.460
And then that's it.

00:17:48.460 --> 00:17:49.720
You just put it in the oven.

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:51.389
You bake it
off.

00:17:51.389 --> 00:17:56.730
You can cool it, and then it will pop right
out and turn into this, and then you can slice

00:17:56.730 --> 00:17:59.629
it, and sauce it, and
serve it.

00:17:59.629 --> 00:18:10.110
So if I were having you over for dinner, and
I was going to plate the bread pudding, what

00:18:10.110 --> 00:18:13.499
we do at the
store and what I like to do is to take some

00:18:13.499 --> 00:18:17.970
vanilla anglaise, which is in the book, and
the chocolate sauce, it's in

00:18:17.970 --> 00:18:23.990
the book as well, and I just, I'm pretty simple,
I like to just sort of swirl them and marble

00:18:23.990 --> 00:18:34.919
the plate, and then
take a scoop of the bread pudding that's nice

00:18:34.919 --> 00:18:48.980
and warm and you can also microwave this if
you want, it really depends

00:18:48.980 --> 00:18:56.299
what size you want, you get a little bit larger
at Extraordinary Desserts, and then I tend

00:18:56.299 --> 00:19:06.090
to go in the yard and grab
whatever's growing, edible or not, and then

00:19:06.090 --> 00:19:12.220
I put that on the side of the plate, and then
if you want, I mean, it

00:19:12.220 --> 00:19:18.570
depends how fussy you want to get... if you
want to sprinkle the powdered sugar on the

00:19:18.570 --> 00:19:19.570
side of the plate.

00:19:19.570 --> 00:19:24.679
This is a
tea strainer, a fork, the sugar and you can

00:19:24.679 --> 00:19:27.460
do it on anything you like.

00:19:27.460 --> 00:19:34.940
And then, basically, you have a finished
product that you can serve, and then the same

00:19:34.940 --> 00:19:41.460
thing goes likewise for if you're building
the mousse in the cup, it's

00:19:41.460 --> 00:19:47.260
from the Yvoire, it's a white chocolate mousse
that's in a cake in the book.

00:19:47.260 --> 00:19:51.679
You can build your white chocolate
mousse, put your fresh berries in the center,

00:19:51.679 --> 00:19:54.890
and then some more white chocolate mousse
and then I finished it off

00:19:54.890 --> 00:19:59.499
with some raspberry gelee, which could be
the raspberry sauce in the book with a little

00:19:59.499 --> 00:20:01.110
gelatin in it.

00:20:01.110 --> 00:20:04.549
And then if
you want to put strawberries on it, and raspberries,

00:20:04.549 --> 00:20:15.049
or if you just want, you could take, a rose,
and my staff gets

00:20:15.049 --> 00:20:22.450
crazy, they love the flowers, so we just do
whatever however, there's no absolute.

00:20:22.450 --> 00:20:27.279
It's just pick colors you like and
kind of go for it.

00:20:27.279 --> 00:20:32.070
And then I use that same gel that I used on
the top, and I just paint the strawberry so

00:20:32.070 --> 00:20:35.429
it looks
like it's more luscious, and then you can

00:20:35.429 --> 00:20:40.239
put that on there, and if you're really going
for it, and it's Valentine's

00:20:40.239 --> 00:20:47.899
Day, and so you break out the edible twenty
three and three quarter gold leaf,

00:20:47.899 --> 00:20:50.659
[audience laughs]

00:20:50.659 --> 00:20:54.090
and then you end up with a cup like that.

00:20:54.090 --> 00:20:59.139
So it's pretty easy, you can use the gold
on your plate, "Good morning

00:20:59.139 --> 00:21:01.649
honey, here's your croissant and your jam"
and put the gold on the croissant.

00:21:01.649 --> 00:21:02.649
[audience laughs]

00:21:02.649 --> 00:21:08.299
I mean you know, so the book is meant to give
you lots of artistic freedom, and just give

00:21:08.299 --> 00:21:12.950
you color options and ways
to think about presenting things that make

00:21:12.950 --> 00:21:16.070
people really want to eat it.

00:21:16.070 --> 00:21:20.610
So, what else can I answer before we're
going to eat?

00:21:20.610 --> 00:21:21.950
[audience laughs]

00:21:21.950 --> 00:21:25.630
&gt;&gt;female #4: Hi, thank you for coming today.

00:21:25.630 --> 00:21:27.350
I have two questions.

00:21:27.350 --> 00:21:31.429
One is that I see you have
graduated from Le Cordon Bleu and you travel

00:21:31.429 --> 00:21:37.230
back to Paris frequently, where would you
recommend for a great

00:21:37.230 --> 00:21:40.460
croissant or desserts in Paris?

00:21:40.460 --> 00:21:43.720
&gt;&gt;Karen: Let's see.

00:21:43.720 --> 00:21:48.350
The one that I was at that was my favorite
this last time , I went and I bought four

00:21:48.350 --> 00:21:50.799
pieces
of cake and I ate all four of them.

00:21:50.799 --> 00:21:51.799
[audience laughs]

00:21:51.799 --> 00:21:55.190
In the same few hours.

00:21:55.190 --> 00:22:02.489
It's called, Le Reve de Patisserie.

00:22:02.489 --> 00:22:04.440
And you can always email me, but that was
like my

00:22:04.440 --> 00:22:08.859
very favorite and then of course I went to
a few more and bought a few pieces and ate

00:22:08.859 --> 00:22:12.429
those you know because I'm
dissecting, but that one was really wonderful.

00:22:12.429 --> 00:22:13.529
&gt;&gt;female #4: Awesome.

00:22:13.529 --> 00:22:15.460
I'll be there really soon so--

00:22:15.460 --> 00:22:16.460
&gt;&gt;Karen: Great.

00:22:16.460 --> 00:22:20.850
&gt;&gt;female #4: The second question is, do you
use ultra pasteurized milk and cream and if

00:22:20.850 --> 00:22:26.149
you do, do you
find a difference in the taste, in your desserts?

00:22:26.149 --> 00:22:29.490
&gt;&gt;Karen: Well, I'm not sure if it's ultra
pasteurized.

00:22:29.490 --> 00:22:31.450
It's organic milk that we use.

00:22:31.450 --> 00:22:37.440
We use all organic milk, and
for the heavy whipping cream, it is ultra

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:40.049
pasteurized.

00:22:40.049 --> 00:22:43.779
I don't know that it has a better flavor,
I know that the

00:22:43.779 --> 00:22:50.409
cream that we use has a higher fat content,
so that means it might have more flavor.

00:22:50.409 --> 00:22:54.230
I do like to use organic
products whenever I can.

00:22:54.230 --> 00:23:00.129
It was absolutely not affordable to have the
cream organic, we did the math on it, and

00:23:00.129 --> 00:23:02.470
it
became thirty five hundred dollars extra a

00:23:02.470 --> 00:23:04.669
month to make that switch.

00:23:04.669 --> 00:23:08.970
And so, if I had to pass that on to my clients,
I'd have to probably be shutting my doors.

00:23:08.970 --> 00:23:13.440
So you know, you just do what you can with
organics, but flavor wise, I

00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:18.179
think we're pretty happy with the product
that we use, and it is ultra pasteurized.

00:23:18.179 --> 00:23:19.179
&gt;&gt;female #4: Thank you.

00:23:19.179 --> 00:23:20.179
&gt;&gt;Unknown speaker2: I have another question.

00:23:20.179 --> 00:23:23.139
How do you roll the chocolate like that?

00:23:23.139 --> 00:23:34.250
&gt;&gt;Karen: Well this we take a tray like, this
kind of a tray and we stick it in the oven

00:23:34.250 --> 00:23:36.809
just to heat it just a
little bit till it's just kind of warm to

00:23:36.809 --> 00:23:42.309
touch, and then we have our liquid chocolate
and then we sort of put it

00:23:42.309 --> 00:23:47.590
over the top here and once it just starts
to cool, we can put it in the refrigerator,

00:23:47.590 --> 00:23:50.999
we pull it out and we wait for
it to get a little bit like tacky, and then

00:23:50.999 --> 00:23:53.309
you use like a paint scraper.

00:23:53.309 --> 00:23:55.359
And, I think that's in the book.

00:23:55.359 --> 00:23:56.649
It is in
the book.

00:23:56.649 --> 00:24:02.519
Yeah, I'm like, I can't remember, what.

00:24:02.519 --> 00:24:04.770
Anybody else?

00:24:04.770 --> 00:24:09.120
All right.

00:24:09.120 --> 00:24:16.279
So I think I am having a helper come and help
me plate, right?

00:24:16.279 --> 00:24:19.919
So, what I'll do too is I can start cutting
some

00:24:19.919 --> 00:24:22.970
of the cakes, 'cause I think we can do that
before--

00:24:22.970 --> 00:24:23.970
&gt;&gt;female #4: Can we tell us what everything
is?

00:24:23.970 --> 00:24:25.229
&gt;&gt;Karen: Oh that's a good point.

00:24:25.229 --> 00:24:30.090
[claps hands together] So the cake over here
on the far right is a Linzer, and it's

00:24:30.090 --> 00:24:33.869
in the book and it's actually is in the holiday
section.

00:24:33.869 --> 00:24:38.629
The book is split between seasons,every quarter,
summer,

00:24:38.629 --> 00:24:40.470
winter, that sort of thing.

00:24:40.470 --> 00:24:42.840
This is in winter.

00:24:42.840 --> 00:24:46.539
It's white chocolate buttercream with hazelnut
almond cakes with

00:24:46.539 --> 00:24:49.519
fresh raspberries and then a homemade raspberry
jam.

00:24:49.519 --> 00:24:55.559
So it has sort of an Austrian play on it with
all the nuts in

00:24:55.559 --> 00:24:56.559
it.

00:24:56.559 --> 00:25:01.090
It's a wonderful wedding cake because as it
sits out at room temperature, the nuts and

00:25:01.090 --> 00:25:04.429
the white chocolate sort
of warm up, so it's a great cake to drive

00:25:04.429 --> 00:25:05.830
from San Diego to L.A.

00:25:05.830 --> 00:25:08.080
It has no problem making that trip.

00:25:08.080 --> 00:25:09.080
[audience laughs]

00:25:09.080 --> 00:25:12.999
And then next to it are some of these white
chocolate mousses, with the raspberries on

00:25:12.999 --> 00:25:14.289
it.

00:25:14.289 --> 00:25:19.669
And then we have the bread
pudding, and this is probably the most popular

00:25:19.669 --> 00:25:24.100
cake at the store, it's called the Viking,
and it has a chocolate crème

00:25:24.100 --> 00:25:27.720
brulee in the bottom of it, and then a milk
chocolate whipped cream, and chocolate pralines

00:25:27.720 --> 00:25:30.029
in it, and chocolate
cake.

00:25:30.029 --> 00:25:35.580
It's called the Viking because it's pretty
intense, it's hearty, and again this is another

00:25:35.580 --> 00:25:38.970
one that's really
easy to take from San Diego to L.A. and not

00:25:38.970 --> 00:25:40.419
have any problem.

00:25:40.419 --> 00:25:43.840
I travel everywhere around the world with
a cake, I

00:25:43.840 --> 00:25:48.149
mean, that's just what, if I'm going somewhere,
people , that's just sort of my calling card.

00:25:48.149 --> 00:25:52.690
So I tend to make
things that can make long drives, and the

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:56.570
ones that are the whipped creams and the fruits
and the berries, you can

00:25:56.570 --> 00:26:01.479
still drive that from San Diego up to this
area because it's only out for two hours,

00:26:01.479 --> 00:26:05.059
as long as it's not Santa Anna
and a hundred degrees out and you're stuck

00:26:05.059 --> 00:26:07.190
in traffic for four hours.

00:26:07.190 --> 00:26:10.720
So even though they're cakes, they're not
that

00:26:10.720 --> 00:26:11.720
fragile.

00:26:11.720 --> 00:26:12.720
You know?

00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:14.830
You shouldn't be scared of them, in terms
of--

00:26:14.830 --> 00:26:17.519
&gt;&gt;female #5: What is that in?

00:26:17.519 --> 00:26:18.519
&gt;&gt;Karen: What is what in?

00:26:18.519 --> 00:26:19.519
&gt;&gt;female #5: The cake when you are traveling.

00:26:19.519 --> 00:26:20.519
&gt;&gt;Karen: Oh, in a box.

00:26:20.519 --> 00:26:21.860
&gt;&gt;Unknown speaker: Just in a box?

00:26:21.860 --> 00:26:27.609
&gt;&gt;Karen: Each of these cakes is on a cardboard
bottom, and then it is usually on a doily,

00:26:27.609 --> 00:26:30.620
cardboard round and then it
just goes in a cardboard box.

00:26:30.620 --> 00:26:32.729
So it's pretty easy.

00:26:32.729 --> 00:26:38.330
I once went to Sydney for New Year's, and
the plane stopped in

00:26:38.330 --> 00:26:44.039
Honolulu, I got out, checked into a hotel
for half a day, put the cake into the refrigerator,

00:26:44.039 --> 00:26:48.029
went for a run, came
back, got the cake, boarded the plane for

00:26:48.029 --> 00:26:52.460
Sydney and showed up for the New Year's party,
and it was the Linzer, and it

00:26:52.460 --> 00:26:53.460
was perfect.

00:26:53.460 --> 00:26:54.460
[audience laughs]

00:26:54.460 --> 00:26:57.879
I got the flowers in Honolulu, I remember
that.

00:26:57.879 --> 00:26:59.120
So you can.

00:26:59.120 --> 00:27:00.129
Yeah, they travel.

00:27:00.129 --> 00:27:01.470
&gt;&gt;female #5: You have to do it as carry on?

00:27:01.470 --> 00:27:04.799
&gt;&gt;Karen: They don't ship, but they do travel,
yeah.

00:27:04.799 --> 00:27:09.009
So unless there's any other questions, I'll
start cutting and--

00:27:09.009 --> 00:27:10.009
&gt;&gt;Unknown male speaker 2:Just one question,
I am curious , you said you went to school

00:27:10.009 --> 00:27:16.539
and how did you decide cakes
was the thing you wanted to do?

00:27:16.539 --> 00:27:23.999
&gt;&gt;Karen: Well, I think 'cause when I was in
college I was so entrenched in science, that

00:27:23.999 --> 00:27:28.059
this other side started
to happen, and I think from being-- my mom

00:27:28.059 --> 00:27:31.850
was a great entertainer, so I think that early
on in life, and my

00:27:31.850 --> 00:27:38.200
grandmothers were as well, and I've always
been a vegetarian so learning to be a chef

00:27:38.200 --> 00:27:42.590
with meat stocks and things
like that did not interest me.

00:27:42.590 --> 00:27:45.210
And this just seemed like a painter's palette.

00:27:45.210 --> 00:27:49.590
You know, all the color and after
having lived in Honolulu and then I lived

00:27:49.590 --> 00:27:53.450
in Mexico, and as well in Paris.

00:27:53.450 --> 00:27:57.659
I mean those are really very colorful,
bountiful places, smells and you know, so.

00:27:57.659 --> 00:27:59.379
&gt;&gt;Unknown male speaker 2: Now do you find
that a lot of inspiration for your designs

00:27:59.379 --> 00:28:09.649
that you make from places you
visit or where do you find a lot of inspiration?

00:28:09.649 --> 00:28:15.510
&gt;&gt;Karen: It's not good for me to be landlocked,
you know I do have to get out quite a bit.

00:28:15.510 --> 00:28:20.489
I can find inspiration
pretty much anywhere I go, even if it's just

00:28:20.489 --> 00:28:25.139
a Sunday at home with some magazines, but
I really find the most

00:28:25.139 --> 00:28:27.039
inspiration in Asia.

00:28:27.039 --> 00:28:35.399
In Asian countries, I mean I love Bali, just
the use of the different freshly grown clove

00:28:35.399 --> 00:28:39.549
and
you know the coffee beans there, and the flowers

00:28:39.549 --> 00:28:44.200
and the essences and teas, that's a great
place, but really anywhere

00:28:44.200 --> 00:28:48.909
where I get away from my regular day to day
job and people being able to call me with

00:28:48.909 --> 00:28:53.340
the random break downs of a
restaurant.

00:28:53.340 --> 00:29:00.090
Because I have a hundred ten employees, and
I'm a sole proprietor so it's kind of a heavy

00:29:00.090 --> 00:29:03.879
burden on the
back some days, so if I can just get away,

00:29:03.879 --> 00:29:08.822
even just-- it took me four planes to get
back to San Diego from Paris this

00:29:08.822 --> 00:29:14.159
last trip, because it was just a real mess,
and I was fine, because I'm like reading my

00:29:14.159 --> 00:29:18.779
books, some new recipes, I
brought all these French books back and I'm

00:29:18.779 --> 00:29:23.700
like five hours in Madrid, not a problem,
you know, oh and overnight

00:29:23.700 --> 00:29:31.029
in in New York, okay, so just being by myself
and quiet, is inspirational.

00:29:31.029 --> 00:29:32.289
So.

00:29:32.289 --> 00:29:40.789
&gt;&gt;Unknown male speaker 3: So the lemon ricotta
cake is by far my favorite, I like all the

00:29:40.789 --> 00:29:42.479
citrus flavors in it.

00:29:42.479 --> 00:29:47.119
Where did you start or what were your interests
when you started and how have they progressed

00:29:47.119 --> 00:29:48.230
over time?

00:29:48.230 --> 00:29:50.950
&gt;&gt;Karen: Well, in terms of flavors?

00:29:50.950 --> 00:29:52.239
&gt;&gt;Unknown male speaker 3: Yeah.

00:29:52.239 --> 00:30:00.119
&gt;&gt;Karen: The lemon ricotta is one of the older,
there's a family of ricottas, there's the

00:30:00.119 --> 00:30:03.340
lemon ricotta, the
passion fruit ricotta, and the blood orange

00:30:03.340 --> 00:30:07.580
ricotta, and most of my cakes come from family
members or friends having

00:30:07.580 --> 00:30:11.790
a birthday and I don't feel like bringing
the same stock cake, so I kinda have to come

00:30:11.790 --> 00:30:13.389
up with something.

00:30:13.389 --> 00:30:17.139
So a lot of
the same cakes are used, but a lot of other

00:30:17.139 --> 00:30:20.710
different flavor conceptions are put together
with them.

00:30:20.710 --> 00:30:27.190
I think when I
started, I probably was a little more straightforward

00:30:27.190 --> 00:30:30.440
with my flavors because I was living in Mexico,
and it was

00:30:30.440 --> 00:30:35.409
back before they were able to import a lot
of things, so I got lemon, and I was able

00:30:35.409 --> 00:30:40.770
to get hazelnuts, so my Linzer
was a little bit different, but the Linzer's

00:30:40.770 --> 00:30:44.279
been around for about twenty-two years, the
lemon ricotta as well,

00:30:44.279 --> 00:30:45.440
because it was easy to do there.

00:30:45.440 --> 00:30:50.139
I think now I'm a little more, I get a little
more out there, but I still think of

00:30:50.139 --> 00:30:54.760
my general audience, and I mean , San Diego's
very different than Los Angeles, I mean, I

00:30:54.760 --> 00:30:59.429
always call us a big
village, so I don't want to get too esoteric

00:30:59.429 --> 00:31:01.169
because that can scare people away.

00:31:01.169 --> 00:31:10.350
So, even Matcha tea mousse has been
an interesting concept and yuzu and I'm trying

00:31:10.350 --> 00:31:14.090
to think, we don't do well with chestnuts,
making things with

00:31:14.090 --> 00:31:19.279
chestnuts, and pear's not a big thing, so
I have to be careful.

00:31:19.279 --> 00:31:22.470
And if something doesn't sell, we don't make
it

00:31:22.470 --> 00:31:23.470
again.

